nib.text:
Protesters gathered outside of the Brooklyn Center Police Department for a fourth night following the shooting death of Daunte Wright.

Citizen users shared videos of the demonstrators interacting with police. 

According to officials with Operation Safety Net (OSN), objects were thrown at law enforcement and some people were trying to climb the fence around the building. Police responded by deploying chemical irritants into the crowd.

The gathering was declared an unlawful assembly around 9 p.m. Police began to issue dispersal orders.

Additional Minnesota National Guard and Minnesota State Patrol officers arrived in the area as the 10 p.m. curfew was going into effect.

The curfew in Brooklyn Center and nearby Brooklyn Park remains in place until 6 a.m. Thursday.

results.raw: Protest Outside Brooklyn Center Police Department at 6624 Humboldt Ave N, Minneapolis, Minnesota, 55430
results.rawLocation: 6624 Humboldt Ave N, Minneapolis, Minnesota, 55430
results.title: Protest Outside Brooklyn Center Police Department

-MYCUgAVxaa6I78zxnUL.text: Incident reported at 6624 Humboldt Ave N.

-MYCUghfxvkqY7_tDlu1.text: Citizen user KobeBryant248 shows video of people gathered where a speaker is speaking.

-MYCfEFgZrRh66aH2hc0.text: Citizen user video shows many people marching.

-MYCo9W7nXtnbaf2P5bk.text: Police report that there are approximately 300 people in front of the Brooklyn Center Police Department.

-MYCodqqmph18volhwax.text: A Citizen user has reported that police presence has increased near Bass Lake Rd & Xerxes Ave N.

-MYCy-1iEJ20lI3WAffE.text: Police state that about 400-500 protesters are in the area with vehicles blocking Humboldt Avenue. The crowd is beginning to "get confrontational" with law enforcement.

-MYD2NiEoGLXrKGSopzT.text: According to police, sheriff's department personnel has deployed crowd-dispersal equipment.

-MYDFQK6UpWRXCP78slC.text: Police have pushed protesters slightly north of the Brooklyn Center Police Department and may soon begin making arrests.

-MYDFm8Mm8wSKA2MxsP5.text: It has been reported that the protesters have stopped throwing projectiles at law enforcement.

-MYDJhr7KlkGi6UZy8kF.text: Video by a Citizen user shows a large police line blocking off nearby traffic and surrounding the Brooklyn Center Police Department.

-MYDL6hzUFuIpVs4ZDsS.text: On the scene footage shows protesters pleading with police to be allowed to leave and cross the police line before the 10 p.m. curfew.

-MYDLgLeNz6GFjG2GquK.text: Aviation units are hovering over the scene at the Brooklyn Center Police Department.

-MYDQRXJWLLKoEkr1rRg.text: Video by a Citizen user shows an officer from the Sheriff's Department saying that police will be leaving the area and clearing a path for protesters to access their vehicles and leave. The National Guard will remain present after police leave the scene.

-MYDTj39O9gRPp7c2Sw4.text: An officer stated that he was shot at south of the scene at the Brooklyn Center Police Department. UPDATE: Officials have not confirmed if any shots were fired during the protests.

nib.text:
Police made upwards of 60 arrests after the 10:00 p.m. curfew went into effect in Brooklyn Center Tuesday night, police said.

Earlier in the evening, a "Justice for Daunte Wright" rally was held. 

The group marched to the FBI building in Brooklyn Center and then back to the police department in the third night of protests since Daunte Wright was fatally shot by a former Brooklyn Center police officer during a traffic stop.

According to officials, demonstrators aimed fireworks and laser pointers, causing police to issue an order to disperse.

Police say some demonstrators began to throw debris at officers. 

At least 60 people were arrested in Brooklyn Center, for behavior described by a state police spokesperson as riotous and criminal. They were to be booked at Hennepin County jail on various charges.

In Minneapolis, two arrests were made for curfew violations.

There were no reports of looting in Minneapolis Tuesday night.

nib.text:
Demonstrators gathered outside of the Brooklyn Center Police Department Monday night, one day after Daunte Wright was shot and killed by police during a traffic stop.

A 7 p.m. curfew went into effect in Hennepin County and the surrounding counties of Anoka, Dakota, and Ramsey.

Hundreds of people remained after curfew outside of the police building, which was fenced off, despite multiple dispersal orders from law enforcement. 

Video from local media and those in the crowd showed law enforcement deploying tear gas and flash-bang canisters.

Officers warned that curfew violations would result in misdemeanor charges for anyone arrested.

In a midnight press conference, officials said that police made about 40 arrests ranging from curfew violation to riotous behavior. 

According to officials, a several officers suffered minor injuries due to thrown debris. 

Officials said that they were unaware of any injuries to protesters Monday night. 

Minneapolis Police officials said that five businesses in Minneapolis were burglarized, including a liquor store, a Target Express, a tobacco store, an AutoZone and a shoe store.

nib.text:
Minneapolis and St. Paul will not be under curfew Wednesday night.

However, local officials announced Brooklyn Center, and Brooklyn Park will have curfews in effect from 10 p.m. until 6 a.m. Thursday. 

Law enforcement officials have advised area residents they may see an increased presence of military vehicles and National Guardsmen in their neighborhoods as they work on protecting people, preventing property destruction, and preserving the conditions for peaceful protest.

Curfews have been in place in the metro area since Daunte Wright was fatally shot by police in Brooklyn Center on Sunday night.
